<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-trigonometric-functions">
  <title>Trigonometric functions</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
           Model periodic behavior by linking a function to the negative of its second derivative.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use numerical methods to reconstruct sine and cosine from basic motion information.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Compute derivatives and antiderivatives of the standard trigonometric functions.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Simple harmonic motion:
        <me>
          y''(t)=-ky(t)
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Can't use slope fields, but can use a modified Euler's method to reconstruct the curve given initial conditions on <m>y</m> and <m>y'</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Define <m>\sin x</m> as the solution to <m>y''=-y</m> with <m>y(0)=0</m> and <m>y'(0)=1</m>, and define <m>\cos x</m> as the solution to the same differential equation with <m>y(0)=1</m> and <m>y'(0)=0</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Can show that <m>\DS\dv{x} \sin x=\cos x</m> by letting <m>C(x)=\DS\dv{x} \sin x</m> and noticing that <m>C</m> also satisfies the same differential equation and has the same initial conditions as <m>\cos x</m>. Similarly, can show that <m>\DS\dv{x} \cos x=-\sin x</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Other properties such as the sum/difference identities and the fact that <m>\sin^2 x + \cos^2 x = 1</m> can also be shown by using the differential equation and initial conditions.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Quotient Rule on <m>\sin x</m> and <m>\cos x</m> gives the derivatives of the other trig functions:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow> \dv{x}\tan x \amp = \sec^{2} x \amp \dv{x}\sec x \amp = \sec x \tan x</mrow>
        <mrow> \dv{x}\cot x \amp = -\csc^{2} x \amp \dv{x}\csc x \amp = -\csc x \cot x</mrow>
      </md>

      <p>
        Every one of these can be thought of backwards to become an antiderivative formula.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Briefly consider damped harmonic motion:
        <me>
          \ee^{-at}\cos bt
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
